### ============================================================
### INSTRUMENT: Psychological Safety Scale (Edmondson, 1999)
### Developer: Amy C. Edmondson, Harvard Business School
### Published: Administrative Science Quarterly, 44(2), 350–383
### Format: 7 Likert-scale items (1–7) | Normative scoring
### Subscale: psychological_safety (single construct)
### Level: TEAM (individual responses aggregated to team mean)
### Admin time: 3–5 minutes
### ============================================================
###
### ⚠ NEW SCHEMA REQUIREMENTS FOR THIS INSTRUMENT:
###
###   "scale_range": { "min": 1, "max": 7, "labels": {...} }
###     Edmondson's original scale uses a 7-point Likert range, NOT
###     the 5-point range used by ROCI-II or the 6-point used by CDP.
###     The API must render the correct number of scale points and
###     avoid collapsing to a different range.
###
###   "reverse_scored": true
###     Items q1, q2, and q6 are reverse-scored in Edmondson's
###     original instrument. The scoring engine must subtract the
###     raw response from (max + 1) = 8 before averaging.
###     Failure to reverse-score these items inverts the construct
###     and produces meaningless or dangerously misleading results.
###
###   "reverse_score_formula": "max_plus_one_minus_raw"
###     Explicit formula tag for the scoring engine to avoid ambiguity
###     across instruments with different scale ranges. Formula:
###     reversed = (scale_range.max + 1) - raw_response
###
###   "aggregation_method": "team_mean"
###     Unlike rwg used in de Dreu, Edmondson validated aggregation
###     using simple team mean with ICC verification. The API should
###     compute team mean after individual reverse-scoring is applied.
###
###   "minimum_respondents_per_team": 3
###     Same as de Dreu instrument — team aggregates require minimum
###     respondent counts for statistical meaningfulness.
###
###   "single_construct": true
###     Psychological Safety Scale measures one latent construct.
###     No subscale routing is needed. A single team-level score
###     is the primary output. Coaches receive percentile and
###     raw mean with confidence interval.
###
###   "benchmarks": { "low": ..., "moderate": ..., "high": ... }
###     Edmondson (1999) and subsequent replications (Google 2015)
###     provide reference distributions. Score thresholds are
###     used to generate interpretive text in coaching reports.
###
### ============================================================

